<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-839-964  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 839 964.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 3 1990 v4 n32 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM decision sparks debate on standing. (Comment) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Witcher, Julie L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Vendors are confused by recent changes in judicial interpretationof the Brooks Act, having to do with who may file or intervene inbid protests.andP;  In Dec 1990, IBM filed papers to protest the awardof a Government Printing Office contract, but the federal courtargued that a protester had to have a direct economic interest inthe outcome of the protest, under the Brooks Act.andP;  IBM was neithersecond in line for the contract nor had they bid at all.andP;  However,according to the ruling, a vendor must intend to submit an offerin response to the solicitation of a bid, or if the due date ispast, they must have submitted one.andP;  In addition, the vendor musthave a direct economic interest in the contract.andP;  Congress shoulddetermine whether it is more important for government contractorsto redress injustices in the system or ensure that only partieswith economic stakes in the outcome participate in a protest.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (contracts).andO;Statute:   Brooks Act (rules and regulations).andO;Topic:     Government RegulationGovernment ContractsEthicsUnited States. Congress.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>